properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions are being reported across the Kivalliq this evening as a deep low pressure system to the east and a strong ridge of high pressure to the west combine to give northwest winds gusting as high as 70 km/h, with widespread poor to near-zero visibilities throughout the region. Blizzard conditions are expected to ease later overnight for Rankin Inlet, Whale Cove and Chesterfield Inlet, but will continue through much of Sunday in Coral Harbour and Naujaat. Bitterly cold air will result in wind chill values approaching the -60 mark tonight before moderating Sunday afternoon. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Blizzard warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 6 hours. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. Moist Pacific air in advance of a low pressure system tracking near the international border will spread snow into central Manitoba beginning this evening. Snow, at times heavy, will continue tonight and Sunday as this slowly moving low lingers in the area until Sunday night. General amounts across central Manitoba will be in the 10 to 20 cm range, though the largest snowfall amounts are expected in a narrow band between The Pas and Swan river areas where up to 25 cm will be possible. properties.Title: Blizzard Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with poor visibility in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. Blizzard conditions are expected tonight in Cape Dorset and on Sunday in Iqaluit as a strong low pressure system crosses southern Baffin Island. Cape Dorset will see blizzard conditions develop later this evening as the low to the east and the high to the west bring northern winds in between gusting up to 80 km/h resulting in near zero visibility in snow and blowing snow. The blizzard should end Sunday morning. Iqaluit will see very strong northwest winds gusting to 90 km/h develop on Sunday as the low pressure system moves to the east. Near zero visibility can be expected in snow and blowing snow. The blizzard should end early Monday morning. Both communities will see wind chill values fall to near -46 during the blizzard. ### Travel is expected to be hazardous due to reduced visibility. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to NUstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #NUStorm.

properties.Title: Extreme Cold Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: A period of very cold wind chills continues. Extreme cold wind chill values of -45 to -50 return tonight as bitterly cold arctic air settles over northern Manitoba in the wake of a departing low pressure system. Although winds in the area have diminished, the extreme cold is likely to return briefly tonight into Sunday morning as the cold airmass remains in place for another day. ### Risks are greater for young children, older adults, people with chronic illnesses, people working or exercising outdoors, and those without proper shelter. properties.Title: Special Weather Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: An intense low pressure system will bring significant amounts of rain beginning Monday evening through Tuesday evening over Southern and Central Quebec. Further north, snowfall amounts of 15 to 25 centimetres are possible from Monday morning to Tuesday evening in a corridor stretching from Abitibi towards Chaleur Bay, including Quebec City. Snow accompanied by moderate winds may reduce visibilities locally in blowing snow. Freezing rain is likely in the vicinity of the snow-to-rain transition area. A more important episode of freezing rain is also likely for areas of the St. Lawrence Valley between Montreal and Quebec City. Travel could be difficult, especially at rush hour Tuesday morning. There is still much uncertainty about the track of this system and thus about the type and amount of precipitation expected. Please stay tuned for future forecasts. ### Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to QCstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #QCStorm.
Expires: 2020-03-08T19:30:52-00:00

properties.Title: Snowfall Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Snowfall with total amounts of 10 to 20 cm is expected. Moist Pacific air in advance of a low pressure system tracking near the international border will spread snow into central Manitoba beginning this evening. Snow, at times heavy, will continue tonight and Sunday as this slowly moving low lingers in the area until Sunday night. General amounts across central Manitoba will be in the 10 to 20 cm range, though the largest snowfall amounts are expected in a narrow band between The Pas and Swan river areas where up to 25 cm will be possible. To the south, the accompanying cold front will move through southern portions of the province tonight and Sunday morning bringing flurries with a risk of freezing rain. ### Visibility may be suddenly reduced at times in heavy snow. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to MBstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #MBStorm.
